The final energies and velocities of the products of the reaction are then
 measured and the nature of the interaction is inferred.
 There are several important features of the nucleus that can be learned
 from these experiments:
\layout Enumerate

The nucleus is small, about 100,000 times smaller than the atom itself.
\layout Enumerate

Most of the matter and all of the positive charge is located in this tiny
 object.
\layout Enumerate

There exists a force, called the strong force, that is attractive, acts
 only within the volume of the nucleus, and is powerful enough to overcome
 the repulsion between the positive charges concentrated in the nucleus.
 
